This is a marble statue depicting a broad-chested man with a trimmed beard and smoldering eyes. Anyone familiar with anthropology can see features in his face that are vaguely reminiscent of Calishite heritage. He stands tall with his heels together and his knees locked, his right arm akimbo, an old and traditional marriage pose for a groom. A bronze plaque at the base of the monument reads:

Duke James d'Cordor the First: Upon these Shores Prosperity is Founded, Unshifting in Spite of the Tide.

Value.value: Here he is, good old James d'Cordor I, founder of the city that still bears his name. He migrated to this island from some coastal mainland area in the late 9th century with an assembly of nobles, some choice merchants and artisans and a whole crew of peasants. He must have been a romantic fellow because the founding of the city was tied in with a marriage ceremony between himself and a noblewoman of royal blood.

James I, founding duke of the city that still bears his name, was born James d'Cordor in the kingdom of Tethyr in the middle of the 9th century. After the nation was decimated by a plague, supposedly brought about by the crown's poor management of its kingdom, d'Cordor and several other dissidents - most of them strong merchants with ties to the shipping community. Upon finding Amia, they landed on the southern coast and founded the trade city of Cordor with a symbolic marriage between Duke James and his royal bride, Lady Alisande Bormul, named for her great-grandmother. From your readings the marriage had less to do with romance and more to do with a promise of health and fertility in the wake of the plagues that prompted their exodus from Tethyr. It must have been successful, for she bore him nine children.

Duke James d'Cordor founded the city that still bears his name at the end of the 9th century. Some claim it was a plague in Tethyr that prompted his exodus from the mainland with several shipping magnates in tow, but the plague was only a symptom of the larger disease these men saw in their kingdom. In 841, the royal family was slaughtered by a cultist of Bhaal, leaving only Alisande Bormul to rule as queen. So began a succession of female regents known as the Queen's Dynasty, and over time they restructured family laws and property laws in ways that d'Cordor deemed were "much too permissive to the fairer sex". James I founded the city in the same moment as wedding the royal black sheep Alisande Bormul, great-granddaughter of the dynasty's first queen and a believer in the traditional role of the woman in the household, royal or otherwise. She then bore him nine children, cementing not only d'Cordor control of the city but also, in an unsavory way, his dominion over the fairer sex.

== Laws of the Kingdom of Cetha ==


Admittance to Frontier's Rest

    1. To enter, you are not permitted to wear a helmet or hood or use any other method to conceal your identity. Head coverings may be worn after entrance is permitted.
    2. Weapons may be carried or sheathed in city limits, provided weapons are only used in self-defense or at the direction of local law enforcement.
    3. Kingdom personnel may stop you to verify your identity against banishment lists.
    --> 3. 1. Failure to comply with requests from official personnel will result in violation of Criminal Law, point 4.

----------------------------------------


Banishment from Frontier's Rest

    The following creatures are banished and will be killed on sight:
        - Orcs
        - Trolls
        - Undead
        - Yuan-Ti
        - Full-blooded Fiends
        - Gnolls

    1. Individuals listed on the Kingdom's separate banishment list will not be permitted entry.
    2. Only the Magistrate or royal family of Cetha may approve permanent banishment of individuals.
    3. Temporary banishment of 24 hours may be given by guards and official personnel of the Kingdom of Cetha.
    4. Individuals who have been banished have the right to request an appeal. Appeals will be observed by the Magistrate of Law.

----------------------------------------


Criminal Law

    1. Murder and Manslaughter.
    2. Assault.
    3. Thievery, Banditry, and Slavery.
    4. Disturbing the Public Safety and Peace.
    5. Harassment.
    6. Bribery, Extortion, and Blackmail.
    7. Public Indecency.
    8. Vandalism to Public or Private Property.


Spellcasting Law

    1. The casting of offensive spells is prohibited, except in defense of self or others, or for training purposes overseen by Kingdom personnel.
    2. Casting of defensive spells is permitted.
    3. Shapeshifting, either through magic or innate ability, into creatures listed on the banished lists is prohibited.
    --> 3. 1. The shapeshifting individual will be killed on sight.
    4. Summoned creatures may travel with their summoner.
    --> 4. 1. Summoned creatures that infringe on Criminal Law point 4 are prohibited, as determined by guard and official Kingdom personnel.
    --> 4. 2. Summoned creatures that are listed on the banished lists are prohibited and will be killed on sight.
    --> 4. 3. The summoner is responsible for all actions of the summoned creature, including any criminal actions.

Waukeen is known as the Merchant's Friend. She is the deity of trade and coin, giving her blessing to merchants and anyone who seeks to partake in the lifeblood of civilization: commerce. She is said to be enthusiastic and active, thoroughly enjoying the ebb and flow of goods and coin. She teaches to always seek out a good deal, but to be willing to offer coin to beggars and businesses alike - that all may have more coin and share in the splendor and comfort of wealth.
